Salesforce’s Agentforce is a signal that “AI features” are no longer enough. As a founder, your positioning needs to move from “we add AI” to “we own a specific workflow/outcome that AI makes dramatically better.”

What this means:
- Salesforce is turning AI into a platform narrative, which raises the bar for generic copilots.
- Buyers will increasingly expect agentic automation, workflow integration, and measurable ROI.
- If your product overlaps CRM, support, sales ops, or back-office work, you need a sharper wedge.
- The winning story is now: niche problem, unique data/workflow, fast time-to-value, clear control layer.

What to do next:
- Recast your positioning around one painful, repeated job-to-be-done.
- Show why you beat a general agent platform on speed, trust, or specialization.
- Tighten ICP: one team, one workflow, one metric.
- Build proof: before/after workflow, case study, or ROI narrative.
- Prepare objection handling: “Why not just use Salesforce/Agentforce?”

In short: don’t compete as “another agent.” Compete as the best answer to a specific business problem that happens to use agents.

